Regretfully, these two drugs also produce numerous adverse effects in patients, such as nephrotoxicity, azotemia, proteinuria, crystalluria, interstitial nephritis, acute tubular necrosis, increases in the concentrations of creatinine up to 50%, hypo- and hypercalcemia, hypo- and hyper-phosphatemia, and the formation of urogenital ulcers, among others (
 Deray et al., 1989; 
 Sauerbrei, 2016). Because of these effects, it is recommended that patients receiving foscarnet be monitored clinically to control abnormalities in metabolites and electrolytes that may result in the alterations indicated above.
